–Deceased","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1325–Female":"1325–Deceased","1348–1396":"1348–1396","–Male":"Deceased","1348":"1348","1325":"1325","1310":"1310","Abt 1348":"about 1348","1396":"1396","about 1310":"about 1310","Deane, Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Deane, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Oundle, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oundle, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Deane","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Deagánaigh</b> ‘son of the deacon’ (see   Deacon  ). In Tipperary it can be from Gaelic <b>Ó Déaghain</b> ‘descendant of the deacon’. In some other cases the surname is of English origin (see   Dean  ).","English: variant of   Dean  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Digney","meanings":["Scottish, Irish, and English (of Norman origin): habitational name from either of two minor places in France called Digny (in Eure-et-Loir and Loiret).","Irish: from Gaelic <b>Mac an Deaghánaigh</b> ‘son of the deacon’ (see   Deane  )."]},{"name":"Deacon","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>deken</i>, <i>dicoun</i> ‘deacon, a priest's assistant at church services’ (Old French <i>diacne</i>, Old English <i>diacon</i>, <i>dēacon</i>, both ultimately from Late Latin <i>diaconus</i>, from Greek <i>diakonos</i> ‘servant’). Since deacons were in holy orders they would not be permitted to marry (with allowance for those few already married when ordained), so the surname is probably in most cases a secular nickname rather than the name of a church official, perhaps denoting a deacon's servant.","English: variant of   Dicken  .","Irish (Wexford): of English origin (see 1 and 2 above), taken to Ireland in the 17th century. When the Irish surname is not of English origin, it may be an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Deocáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Deocán</i>’, a personal name of uncertain etymology."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Henry Deane was born about 1310, in Deane, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Deane. He had at least 1 daughter with Lady Elizabeth Deane."},"et":{"about 1310–":"umbes 1310–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1348–1396":"1348–1396","–Male":"Surnud","1348":"1348","1325":"1325","1310":"1310","Abt 1348":"umbes 1348","1396":"1396","about 1310":"umbes 1310","Deane, Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Deane, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Oundle, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oundle, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1310–":"noin 1310–Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1348–1396":"1348–1396","–Male":"Kuollut","1348":"1348","1325":"1325","1310":"1310","Abt 1348":"noin 1348","1396":"1396","about 1310":"noin 1310","Deane, Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Deane, Hampshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Oundle, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oundle, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1310–":"environ 1310–Décédé","1310–Male":"1310–Décédé","1325–Female":"1325–Décédée","1348–1396":"1348–1396","–Male":"Décédé","1348":"1348","1325":"1325","1310":"1310","Abt 1348":"environ 1348","1396":"1396","about 1310":"environ 1310","Deane, Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Deane, Hampshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Oundle, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oundle, Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sir Henry Deane est né environ 1310, à Deane, Hampshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Deane. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Lady Elizabeth Deane."},"de":{"about 1310–":"um 1310–Verstorben","1310–Male":"1310–Verstorben","1325–Female":"1325–Verstorben","1348–1396":"1348–1396","–Male":"Verstorben","1348":"1348","1325":"1325","1310":"1310","Abt 1348":"um 1348","1396":"1396","about 1310":"um 1310","Deane, Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Deane, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Oundle, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oundle, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummar